Well might that young girl, standing before a Roman, blush \
and tremble to confess herself one of that despised, down-trodden \
race, the conquered inhabitants of Judzea. The utter destruc- \
tion of Jerusalem had occurred nine years before our story \
opens; hundreds and thousands of Jews and Jewesses had been \
sold for slaves throughout the Roman Empire, until, as their \
great Lawgiver had predicted, \'93no man would buy them.\'94 \
Certainly Aurelia Cotta would never have given six hundred \
drachme, nor even a twentieth part of that sum, for a Jewish \
maiden; and Sophronia might well have feared that on her \
mistress making the discovery that her newly-purchased slave \
was only Grecian by the half-blood, she would immediately \
send her back to Calphurnius. The manner in which her con- \
fession was received, at least by one of the young ladies, scarcely \
tended to reassure her. \
