EFORE Sophronia had been many days in her new \
\
position, Camilla perceived that the numerous slaves \
\
in her father\'92s extensive household had taken as \
\
great a dislike to the new-comer as had been exhi- \
bited by Marcia. The latter, who rejoiced in a new sub- \
ject for conversation, had at once informed those slaves who \
served at her toilet that Sophronia was more Jewish than \
Grecian, and they were not slow in spreading the interesting \
news. Sophronia, on her part, kept as much aloof from them \
as possible. She worked in the ante-chamber into which Ca- \
milla\'92s bedroom opened, and at any part of the day except the \
slaves\'92 meal times, when her young mistress might require her, \
she was certain of finding her in that quiet chamber. Soph- \
ronia herself never uttered a word concerning the ill-treatment \
which she experienced from the other servants, and it was only \
by her persistent seclusion, and by Camilla having once or \
twice caught some of the others in the act of branding Soph- \
ronia with such epithets as \'93 Jewish dog,\'94 \'93 Eastern barbarian,\'94 \
and \'93sucking-pig,\'94 that the mistress could form any idea of \
the petty persecution which the \'91slave-girl experienced at the \
hands of her comrades. To the great distress of her sister, \
Marcia joined in the evil-speaking as much as any one. \
\
