Camilla had several times endeavoured to obtain from the \
slave-girl some further information regarding her parents and her \
early years, but Sophronia quietly, though respectfully, evaded \
her questions. Aurelia also tried to induce her to speak on \
these subjects, but in vain; and Camilla, concluding from this \
that the girl was unwilling to speak of her past life, forbore to \
question her any further. The reticence of Sophronia, never- \
theless, did not lessen the curiosity of her young mistress to \
ascertain something concerning Jewish manners, and especially \
the Jewish religion. Camilla was entirely ignorant respecting \
the latter, having merely heard it spoken of as the \'93superstition \'94 \
of these despised tributaries of the Roman Empire, and having \
understood that Jews were invincibly attached to their own faith, \
did not sacrifice to the Roman gods, and deemed it unlawful to \
eat pork. The number and nature of the gods whom the Jews \
worshipped\'97for the idea of a monotheistic religion never \
occurred to her\'97she specially desired to know; the quality of \
their sacrifices, the nature of their doctrines, and, above all, the \
success or failure of their prayers. On this latter subject Ca- \
milla\'92s mind was frequently employed. Sophronia never uttered \
a word on such matters; and Camilla perceived that she must \
open the question herself. She occupied herself for some days \
In consideration of how this might best be done. \
\
On one of these days, Camilla was busy at work in the ala, \
Sophronia attending on her, when one of the other servants ran \
in hurriedly to inquire if the latter might be permitted to come \
to the side-door of the house, which opened on a narrow street, \
to speak to a stranger who had rung the bell, and whose language \
none of the rest couldcomprehend. They fancied that he must \
be a Greek; might Sophronia speak to him and see? Camilla \
assented, and as only a curtain separated the room in which she \
sat from the passage which led to the side door, she drew aside \
the curtain, and glanced at the stranger. Hewasa young man \
in worn and travel-stained costume and of a foreign appearance. \
When Sophronia reached the door, Camilla noticed that she \
greeted the stranger with \'93Xaize!\'94\'97a word the meaning of \
which the Roman lady well knew, from the circumstance of its \
\
