OMAN ladies never condescended to soil their fair \
fingers with cookery, which they regarded as work \
only fit for slaves. However many pairs of \'91hands \
had been required, therefore, by Actius, he might \
have sighed in vain for those of Aurelia or her daughters. \
\
The kitchen, when Sophronia entered it, was far from being \
either silent orempty. It consisted of two rooms, the inner one \
opening out of the atrium, the outer communicating with the \
street, which in this instance was the Via Sacra. In the outer \
apartment a number of slaves were busied in mixing ingredients, \
cleaning vessels, and conducting the minor or rougher operations \
of cookery, under the superintendence of four important persons \
in the inner kitchen. \'91These were Actius the master-cook, the \
carver, the structor or arranger of dishes, and an elderly female \
slave, the head assistant in this department, who stood rolling \
out pastry, and expressing great satisfaction that \'93that lazy, \
worthless slattern \'94 Sophronia was come at last. \
\
The master-cook, garbed in white, with a long ladle in his hand, \
promenaded the kitchen, issuing very peremptory orders to all in \
his employ, and rather disposed to forget that orders took time \
to execute. Under his instructions, Sophronia proceeded to mix \
the materials for coptz and placente,\'97namely, cheesecakes and \
almond cakes\'97to assist with the peacock, and to help in various \
\
