It was not often that Paratus joined his family at supper, as \
he did on this occasion. A Roman gentleman lived out of doors, \
and was oftenan accomplished diner-out. The ladies were usually \
keepers at home, though they were much less strictly secluded \
than was the custom among the Greeks. On coming into the \
atrium, the master of the house brought with him an amount of \
scent which perfumed the whole area, for he had just left the \
therme. Here a slave was in waiting, with a loose white robe, \
which Paratus put on, having thrown off his pallium. The ladies \
were already in the triclinium when he appeared. He kissed his \
daughters, whom he had not seen since the previous evening ; \
and then reclined himself on one of the couches, leaning on his \
left side, his arm being supported bycushions. Aurelia, inarobe \
of the same loose sort, with ivyin her hair, reposed on the opposite \
couch ; while Marcia took her seat at the feet of her mother, and \
Camilla at those of her father. The attendants were three slave \
boys, dressed in loose tunics. The supper this evening was a \
very meagre one, since every one was busy preparing for to- \
morrow ; and the meal consisted merely of olives, eggs, a couple \
of pheasants, a turbot, a water-rat, and some open tartlets. \
Paratus ate his olives and eggs in silence, but at length, as the \
pheasants were coming in, abruptly asked a rather unexpected \
question. \
\
Well, Domina\'97I suppose it is too late to put off to-morrow\'92s \
banquet ? \'94 \
\
\'93 Quite too late, Domine. It could not be done. But what \
can make you wish to postpone it ?\'94 \
\
\'93Then,\'94 rejoined Paratus, answering categorically, \'91\'91I presume \
we must do as best we can with the other guests. But is it \
not vexatious? Strophius cannot come.\'94 \
\
