Supper being over, Paratus and Aurelia amused themselves by \
taking an evening stroll on the terrace beyond the ecus ; while the \
girls retired to the ala, and resumed their work. Then Paratus \
threw himself on a couch in the atrium, and summoned all the \
slaves to his presence. Any requests, complaints, or necessities \
of any among them, were laid before him ; and having thus passed \
in review before their master, each slave wished him good-night, \
and retired. Aurelia, on hearing from the ala, whither she had \
retreated, their departing footsteps, ordered the girls to bed, and \
\'91going into the atrium, clapped her hands for the attendant slaves. \
It was scarcely yet dark, but the slave-girls, Libia, Flora, and \
Sophronia, brought lamps in their hands, each lighting her respec- \
tive mistress to her chamber. \
\
The bed-chamber to which Camilla, attended by Sophronia, \
repaired for the night, would be considered a very small room \
indeed according to modern ideas of comfort. It was lighted \
by a single window six feet from the floor, and its sole furniture \
consisted of two beds, and one seat placed between them. \'91The \
bedsteads were long and narrow, and raised so high from the \
\'91floor, that three steps were necessary to enable the owner to reach \
her resting-place. Their material was ebony, and they were orna- \
mented with figures in low relief. On the bedstead was laid a \
thick soft feather-bed, and on this a pillow in an embroidered \
pillow-case. There was no bolster. Two quilts covered the bed, \
purple in colour, and embroidered with gold. The other bed was \
rather less richly adorned ; it formed Camilla\'92s sofa by day, and \
