Paratus, in his capacity as priest towards his own household, \
stood ready to officiate at the altar on the north of the atrium. \
The slaves were all assembled in the latter apartment, to which \
Aurelia and her daughters had already repaired. I have said, a// \
the slaves ; but one was absent. Paratus,an easy-tempered man, \
who never troubled himself to interfere with the doings or opinions \
of others so long as they did not clash with his own dignity or \
convenience, had readily acquiesced in Sophronia\'92s timid petition \
that she might absent herself from the household devotions, at \
which, as a Jewess, her religion did not permit her presence. \
Paratus wore a sacrificing robe, and in his right hand he held a \
box of incense.. Each member of his household, approaching \
the altar, took from the box a pinch of the incense, and threw it \
on the flame which burned on the altar, saying as he did so, \'93 Be \
propitious to us, O Jupiter, whether thou art god or goddess.\'94 \
When all had sacrificed, they turned their faces to the east, and \
covered them in their palila, while Paratus recited various prayers, \
the attendants repeating them after him ina lower tone. Then \
followed more sacrifices to various other gods and goddesses, \
concluding with one addressed \'93to the fortunes of Czsar.\'94 \
These over, a hymn of praise was chanted by the younger \
members of the household in honour of Juno, the voices of \
Marcia and Camilla leading the chant. The prayers lasted above \
an hour, and were finished about five a.m. It will be seen that \
even in heathen eyes \'93the sacrifice was not prayer, but a prepara- \
tion for prayer.\'94 The work of the law written in their hearts \
taught even these ignorant men that the Deity must be propitiated \
before He could be petitioned. \
\
