For in that first age of the primitive Church, as it is often \
seen to be in times of persecution, when the hope of Heaven \
was frequently all that a man had of comfort, it was far more \
living and energetic than in our easy times. The Christians \
with furrowed brows, and drawn mouths, and querulous voices, \
do not flourish under Diocletian half so well as under Victoria. \
Oh, what a responsibility is theirs who bring up an evil report \
of the good land, and keep the fresh young spirits of the world \
