began it with them. For the strictly Apostolic practice, I refer \
my readers to the Scriptures themselves. In the period imme- \
diately following, corruptions began to come in; yet a great \
number of these grew slowly. Many points are uncertain; but \
what can be certainly stated with respect to the first century \
is as follows. \
\
With the exception of the use of forms of prayer\'97more or: \
less rigid in different Churches\'97the primitive celebration of \
Divine service and of the Sacraments appears to have greatly \
resembled the present custom of Nonconformist communions, \
The Churches of Rome and Alexandria had always the stiffest, \
most stringent, and most minute ritual of any. But it may \
generally be said that the primitive order was very much more \
elastic than that of the subsequent ages. It was almost free \
from any observance of times and seasons,\'97the Lord\'92s Day \
was the only exception: for not only saints\'92 days, but Christ- \
mas, Lent, and Easter, are of later origin. It had scarcely \
any ceremonies\'97the Sacraments, confirmation, marriage, and \
burial, exhausted the list of rites. The bishop was simply the \
head presbyter of each Church\'97grimus tnler pares\'97and was \
much in the position of a modern rector with several curates. \
The deaconess filled for women the same place as the deacon \
for men, and both were servants of the Church, Baptism took \
place in the round baptistery, which was a vestibule to the \
Church, and was performed either by immersion or suffusion,\'97 \
more frequently the former,\'97but always by the Bishop. Until \
a later date than this, it was the initial rite of the Christian life. \
When it began to be supposed that sin after baptism was hard \
to be forgiven, the natural result followed\'97that baptism was \
postponed, sometimes until the very moment preceding death: \
thus entirely destroying its significance as the witnessing for \
Christ before men. \
\
The Lord\'92s Supper was administered four times in the week. \
Some churches had it on Sunday ; others carefully avoided that \
day. It took place twice in each day, in the early morning \
before dawn, and again in the evening, at the usual hour of \
supper. In the latter case it was often preceded by the Agape, \
or love-feast. All present communicated, those who were not \
