Those who left deliberately, of choice, are the product of a later \
age: for in early times, persons who did not mean to com- \
municate did not attend church at all. The bread, baked in the \
form of the large flat cake usual in the East, and in the Eastern \
half of Europe, was originally broken between two persons ; \
but very early it became the custom for the deacon to break it, \
and hand it to the partaker, It was always taken in the bare \
hand; when the notion arose that it was too sacred to be \
touched, it was received first in a golden vessel, and afterwards \
in a napkin laid over the hand. For the priest to place it in \
the mouth was a much later innovation. The Sacrament was \
administered in both kinds. In times of persecution, some \
congregations substituted water for wine, to avoid betraying their \
hours of celebration to the heathen by the scent of the latter: \
but they were generally censured for doing so. The idea that \
it was wicked to drop a crumb of the consecrated bread seems \
to be one of the earliest superstitions that entered the Church. \
Th\'e9 mixing of water with the wine obtained currency from the \
first, but it arose, not from any doctrinal fancy, but from the \
fact that the ancient wines were syrups, and could be drunk only \
by mixture with water. \
