Two events occurred in the course of the following summer. \
The first was the birth of an infant daughter to Victor and \
Sophronia. To Camilla, scarcely less than to its mother, the \
baby was a source of never-ending delight. Whether awake \
or asleep, laughing or crying, doubling its tiny fists at nothing, \
or gazing at the same object with grave wide-open black eyes \
\'97in all attitudes it presented an admirable model. Sophronia \
did, indeed, suggest a doubt as to whether the human form \
was an allowable object for painting. But on this subject \
Camilla could not see with the eyes of her friend, and she \
maintained that what was forbidden by the Second Command- \
ment was manifestly the painting or carving of objects for \
worship. Victor, to whose decision as umpire both ladies ap- \
pealed, did not give a very conclusive answer. His Christian \
education drew him in one direction, and the natural sym- \
pathies of his Greek feeling in another. He admitted that \
certainly some Christians were of opinion that painting the \
human figure was unlawful; but this was by no means the \
case with all: and he reminded his wife that if the Second \
Commandment were held to forbid the delineation of man for \
other objects beside worship, it must necessarily be considered \
to preclude all painting of any thing: since even a rose or a \
peach was something in earth beneath. In this Sophronia \
acquiesced, but still did not seem convinced on the debated \
point. Camilla, however, gathering from Victor\'92s reply that \
he at any rate did not consider it wrong to paint the baby, \
resumed her brush with an easy conscience. The prenomen \
to be bestowed on the infant was considerably canvassed. \
Sophronia was divided between Berenice and Theodora; \
Victor said little, but in his heart he wished the child to re- \
ceive the name of his Grecian mother, Aglaia. As soon as \
Sophronia guessed this, she waived her own predilections, and \
