When they saw her again on the following morning, they could \
scarcely recognise the Irene who had received them on their \
first coming to Corinth. The beauty, the vivacity, the airy grace, \
which had once distinguished her, were gone. But gone with \
them were the apathy, the scornful pride, the stubborn unbelief. \
Physically, she was very ill; morally, she was gentle, humble, \
docile as a little child. There was no more unwillingness to \
hear the truth\'97no more oppositions of science falsely so called. \
The meek depression of manner was as little like the brilliant \
beauty whom they recalled in her superb saloons, as were the \
thin, pallid, pain-worn features. Only on one point she still, \
though quietly enough, refused to listen, and put away from her \
the comfort which Sophronia strove to pour into her wounded \
soul. She still maintained that God could have no mercy for \
her. That God was, and that He was the rewarder of them \
that diligently seek Him, she now conceded in an instant. But \
no words could move Irene from her conviction, that those who \
had not sought Him, who had denied His being, and stifled \
their own convictions for so long, had no claim to His mercy. \
By degrees they learned that Coriander\'92s last iilness had been \
very short; that Zo\'e9 and her husband had been staying in the \
house at the time; that Adrastus, Zo\'e9\'92s husband, being himself \
learned in the law, and an unscrupulous man, had informed \
Irene, who was too ignorant to be aware whether he spoke the \
truth or not, that she, having once been a slave, had no claim \
whatever upon any part of her husband\'92s property, which \
belonged to Zo\'e9 as his heir-at-law: and that Irene might think \
herself well off that she was permitted to go in peace with her \
own liberty and the clothes which she wore. To add to her \
